Author: Linnaeus, 1758
Critical Notes: "Due to the genetic variability exhibited among isolated populations, Jack Creek’s three spine sticklebacks may be a rare sub-species. This investigation was never followed up" (Keith Erickson pers. comm 2020).

Author: Girard, 1856
Collector/Source: Donald E. McAllister & M. O. Yesaki

Author: (Girard, 1855)
Notes: Reported as Squalus acanthias in CMN catalogue
Critical Notes: Reported as Squalus acanthias (CMNFI 1985-0086.5) in CMN records; Squalus suckleyi replaces Squalus acanthias in the NEP.
Considering the presence of multiple species of Phyllochaetopterus in the Northeast Pacific, some of which are undescribed, Phyllochaetopterus sp. is here reported.

Author: Moore, 1905
Critical Notes: Described from Japan; may not be present in the NEP.

Specimens from the NEP are likely to be mis-identified as this name is a holdover from when European literature dominated polychaete systematics. This species was described from the Arctic, and is a European species. Northern European specimens have a distinct color pattern similar to our Cheilonereis cyclurus, which is very different from NEP worms identified as N. zonata.
Epigamia alexandri (Malmgren, 1867) describes a European species that is likely not present. What is known to be present is Epigamia magna.

Author: Harris (provisional species name)
Critical Notes: Myxicola sp.A = "Myxicola aesthetica"; In Europe, M. infundibulum is found in soft-sediments and M. aesthetica on docks & hard-surfaces. However, specimens from the NEP are morphologically and genetically different. In the past, several species of Myxicola were described from California, Puget Sound, and Alaska. This material needs to be re-examined.

Author: Harris (provisional species name)
Critical Notes: Myxicola sp.B = "Myxicola infundibulum"; In Europe, M. infundibulum is found in soft-sediments and M. aesthetica on docks & hard-surfaces. However, specimens from the NEP are morphologically and genetically different. In the past, several species of Myxicola were described from California, Puget Sound, and Alaska. This material needs to be re-examined.

Author: Johnson, 1901
Critical Notes: Listed in older references as Serpula vermicularis which is a valid species but now restricted in range to Europe.

Author: Örsted, 1843
Critical Notes: Dodecaceria concharum is a European species which may not be present in the NEP; molecular analysis is required to confirm.

Author: Berkeley & Berkeley, 1954
Critical Notes: Dodecaceria fewkesi creates its own calcareous tube while D. concharum burrows into calcareous substrates.

Author: Cuvier, 1827
Critical Notes: Chaetopterus does occur in the region but which species has not yet been documented.

Author: Ortmann, 1890
Critical Notes: Schizoporella japonica is an introduced species in the NEP, although we have at least one other introduced Schizoporella in California. Schizoporella  unicornis is now restricted to Europe." (Jim Carlton pers. comm 2019)

Author: Sanamyan, Sanamyan, McDaniel, Martynov, Korshunova & Bocharova, 2019
Sanamyan & Sanamyan, 2006
Critical Notes: Reported as Urticina crassicornis in collections at the RBCM (986-00197-009). This European species concept is commonly misapplied to U. grebelnyi. See Sanamyan and Sanamyan (2006).

The genus Alcyonium has been documented from both the southern Gulf Islands and from Race Rocks / Browning Passage / Weynton Passage. However, these populations are genetically different and have not yet been circumscribed as species.

Multiple Euphysa species are likely present in the region. "Differences are apparently in the young specimens, but generally we only ever see the adults. Euphysa japonica has four tentacles, all alike, including in the youngest stages. Euphysa flammea has four tentacles as an adult, but it is released with only one tentacle and the rest develop successively. Euphysa tentaculata (which may well be an Arctic species) is said to have one long tentacle, two half as long, and one bulb without tentacles. I’ve noticed Euphysa medusae both in the spring and in the fall (rarely if ever in the summer)—this seasonality suggests the occurrence of two different species.” (Claudia Mills pers. comm. 2020).

"Aequorea victoria is our native species, named nearby, whereas A. forskalea is native to Europe or the East Coast. Sarah Abboud's recent molecular analysis of Pacific coast Aequorea showed they belonged to a 'victoria' clade including many potential species or subspecies. This is a species complex, though Sarah has not published or renamed anything" (Wyatt Patry pers. comm. 2020).
At least two other taxa—A. struthionides and A. latirostris—are expected in the region. The former may be more likely to be observed, though it is impossible to be certain without close examination.

Author: (Agassiz, 1862)
Critical Notes: Reported as Phialidium gregarium in CMN collections, an unaccepted synonym (WoRMS Editorial Board 2021).
At least two species are present in the genus—O. dichotoma and O. longissima—but they cannot be determined in the field.

Author: (Agassiz, 1862)
Collector/Source: Fisheries Research Board of Canada, Nanaimo
Critical Notes: Reported as Halistaura cellularia in CMN collections, an unaccepted synonym (WoRMS Editorial Board 2021).
Sturdy hydroids with alternating zoantheca structures. According to Fraser (1937), numerous species in this genus are known to the region.

Author: Lindsay, 2017
Critical Notes: This cryptic species was recently separated from Aegina citrea. "Everything from surface waters in the Salish Sea is Solmundaegina nematophora" (Claudia Mills pers. comm. 2021)

Two taxa are known in the genus Lepeophtheirus: one associated with salmonids (reported in PMLS records as 'sp.A'); the other with lingcod ('sp.B'). The species associated with lingcod is reported for Galiano Island, though the other species likely also occurs locally.

Author: (Jensen, 1998)
Critical Notes: The genus Pandalus is adopted instead of Pandalopsis as per WoRMS Editorial Board (2021), though there is some contention regarding this matter. "Since generic splits are rather arbitrary, I am not sure why they split off Pandalus lucidirimicolus when all the Pandalopsis fall out together in their tree" (Gregory Jensen pers. comm. 2019).

Author: (Hansen, 1903)
Critical Notes: Accessioned in the RBCM collections as Sergestes similis, an unaccepted synonym (WoRMS Editorial Board 2021).
At least two species are present in the region. Their small sizes, rapid swimming behavior, and minor anatomical differences make field identifications impossible.

Author: (Stimpson, 1862)

Species complex currently under revision.

Author: Kienberger, Carmona, Pola, Padula, Gosliner & Cervera, 2016
(MacFarland, 1966)
Critical Notes: Two subspecies are recognized: a Californian subspecies, Apata pricei pricei, as originally described from Monterey, California, and a Western Pacific subspecies, Apata pricei komandorica. No specimens have been sequenced to determine which subspecies are present in the Salish Sea. However, we do not appear to have the subspecies originally described in MacFarland, 1966.

Author: Korshunova, Fletcher, Picton, Lundin, Kashio, N. Sanamyan, K. Sanamyan, Padula, Schrödl & Martynov, 2020
Critical Notes: Currently, there is a sequence of Cadlina klasmalmbergi from Galiano Island in GenBank, but none of the other species that make up this complex—Cadlina jannanicholsae, Cadlina sylviaearleae or Cadlina luteomarginata—are yet represented. Two of the three other species have been sequenced from BC—C. jannanicholsae and C. luteomarginata. The latter has been sequenced from Alaska and Washington and is therefore likely present in BC. Without more focused collecting and genetic study, however, one cannot be certain of the local diversity.

Author: MacFarland, 1966
Critical Notes: PMLS records list Cadlina luteomarginata complex due to challenges in field identification. However, here we recognize both Cadlina klasmalmbergi and Cadlina luteomarginata based on other confirmed observations. True Cadlina luteomarginata have more conspicuous tubercles and lack yellow glands near the mantle edge. Cadlina klasmalmbergi is more common in BC than C. luteomarginata.

Author: (M. Sars, 1829)
Critical Notes: Coryphella verrucosa was originally described from the Atlantic. Coryphella pseudoverrucosa has since been described in the Western Pacific, but a preliminary genetic comparison shows a difference between the Salish Sea specimens and those from the Western Pacific. Specimens have been collected from BC and WA but the paper confirming their identity has not been published.

Author: (Lambe, 1893)
